column1: Will Ketanji Brown Jackson be confirmed by the Senate before 1 May 2022?
column6: ['Open']

There seems to be no split among the Democrats, and a few Republicans have gotten on board. It's clear that the Republicans have not found anything to hold against her, and have resorted to mere showboating. Things will not change, and she will be confirmed.
Mitt Romeny and GOP votes make this more likely.
with anticipation of vote today and 3 Republicans stating they will vote for her
As of Apr 5 - she has 53 in favor vs 47
Support from 3 republican senators and Democrats ensure confirmation.
Given support from swing democrats and at least one republican, this seems very likely
Good luck and hopes for smooth sailing here
The Republicans' grownup caucus has spoken. She's in.
Confirmation seems imminent this week.
The recent slow drip of support from a few Republican senators for KBJ is indicative that her confirmation should pass.
Looking almost certain that this will be further supported and passed.

Now the big hurdle has passed it is much clearer -but I still expect the GOP to filibuster for the hours - There are still many ways to delay. GOP can still push it or try to after Easter holiday, saying Dems are shoving it through, wait until afterwards. GOP will not want to go home to constituents if she is confirmed. GOP would rather wait until after recess.
Murkowski and Romney on board. Only a Republican filibuster to block at this point it seems.
With Collins stating that she's a yes vote, it's all but over.
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-60986427
A full vote is expected in April, with all Democrats and at least one Republican in her favour.
Yes.
Sounds like this is scheduled and going to happen shortly
Overall, consensus seems to be that this will happen.
The first Republican has hopped on the band wagon.
No reasons anymore to object
Collins is acting iffy no longer; all-in.
Manchin on board, Romney on board. Its a lock if no one strays regardless of Sinema. If Collins or Murkowski join its done.

Repeating my forecast. AP: "The Senate Judiciary Committee has set a vote next week to recommend nominee Ketanji Brown Jackson to the full Senate. Jackson's confirmation as the first Black woman on the Supreme Court appears likely by mid-April." https://twitter.com/AP/status/1508613375105933320
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/03/28/ketanji-brown-jackson-meeting-senators-nomination-judiciary/
Manchin on board and no visible road blocks.
Seems like Manchin is going to go along with her. As long as Democrats stay together, she should be okay

Mostly following the crowd, but bumping down as I suspect many are not fully considering the deadline. From quick wikipedia scan, it seems like this question's deadline allows for the process to be slightly longer than the recent average length of ~54 days. I would guess this one is substantially faster than average given the president's party controls the Senate. Plus we are now well into the hearings with no indications of Democrats breaking with the party. But, the deadline question still injects more uncertainty into this forecast than I think the crowd is accounting for.
With Manchin in, it should happen soon.
"Manchin backs Jackson"
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/25/us/politics/manchin-jackson-supreme-court.html

Aiming for the judiciary committee vote on April 4th (https://www.cnbc.com/2022/03/24/supreme-court-pick-ketanji-brown-jackson-confirmation-what-happens-next.html), Manchin said he'll vote for her (https://www.cnn.com/2022/03/25/politics/joe-manchin-ketanji-brown-jackson-vote/index.html), and nothing substantive came up in the hearings, which eliminates most of the chances for the confirmation to be shot down. Average time from judiciary committee vote to Senate confirmation is 8 days, longest being 16 for Kagan, so this looks like a pretty sure bet at this point.
Republican Senators Say No Boycott Planned for Jackson Committee Vote https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-senators-say-no-boycott-planned-for-jackson-committee-vote-11648148340
Another favorable day of confirmation hearings
The hearings are progressing and there is still no sign the democrats will not meet their early April confirmation timeline.

Likely a bi-partisan vote, but with Democrats holding 50 and all she needs is 51, it is fairly likely she will. The question is when. McConnell says Nay, could mean backroom ways to delay or worse, kick it off completely. That would be too risky given it would demonstrate that the GOP focuses on tweets and having evidence they are derailing a nomination again. (aka. Garland). RBG was 50 days and Barret was slammed in at 30 days. The average is around 70 days for confirmation. If there are no more circus tricks like boycotting the committee, it should be smooth. If games are played, then this will play out longer. April recess will happen, and then the question is how long it takes to bring it to a vote.
Yes, with hearings currently underway, I cannot imagine such a intelligent and qualified candidate will be denied an open seat on the bench within the month of April.
Strong probability that this will happen.

Judge Brown is highly qualified, while there are some senators who might wish to delay a vote but that simply isn't possible since in 2017, Senate Republicans under Majority Leader Mitch McConnell changes the rules to end the filibuster for Supreme Court nominees, which then allowed Neil Gorsuch to be confirmed. On top of this Judge Brown is likely to pick up at least a couple of Republican votes as well.
Democrat controlled
Another non controversial day at the hearings.
It's looking good but there are potential curve balls including the apparent frailty of Clarence Thomas
+20 to follow the crowd, it sounds like the hearings are going well and things seem like they'll proceed fairly quickly.
Seems to be handling herself well, presenting a pleasant contrast to the buffoonery of the Honourable Ted Cruz and the Honourable Josh Hawley. . And when I say "Honourable" I mean "shameless."
Up 5% since I've been below the consensus much of the forecast time.
Seems like a reasonable time scale. But can't really say much about it.
Bumping as navigated day 2 well
She's articulate, has done well so far in the hearings, enough votes, barely to get approved, so far no major objections.

pr(confimed)=pr(announced&confirmed)*pr(on time) pr(announced = 77% 165 nominations for the Court, including those for chief justice. Of this total, 127 were confirmed https://www.senate.gov/legislative/nominations/SupremeCourtNominations1789present.htm

As this nomination wouldn't change the make-up of the court and the optics of opposing the first Black woman nominee are almost certain to quell the voices of Senator Hawley, etc., I give this a very high probability. If Justice Thomas's illness turns out to be more involved than reported as of March 21, however, my prediction would be much lower.
Up 5% for the progress of replacement.

The GOP opened with apophasic "And we're going to mention Kavanaugh by saying we won't be accusing you of raping anyone when you were in high school." That they led with that (I was expecting to hear the "but last time..." sometime after day four) tells me they don't really have anything against Jackson. She'll get confirmed quickly.
This looks like it's a done deal.
Moving slightly right after successful day 1
There are enough votes to confirm her. She was recently vetted for the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.

There are no skeletons in her closet. There are enough votes to have her confirmed. She has been scrutinized and vetted through other appointments and she is the first black female will serve on the Supreme Court. Any opposition to her appointment is not in any way substantial and a flimsy attempt at political posturing.

having read through the other forecasters interpretation of today's hearings and followed the praise by some Repbulicans (in addition to Democrats) I find it unlikely that this will be a heavily partisan vote and should progress ahead of the April 8 break for Congress. I leave some % doubt given any unforeseen delays or in the event of a Democrat missing a couple votes.

Mr. Justice Thomas went into the hospital with some sort of flu thing that he is expected to be done with by like Thursday. This should remind the Ds that they need to get this week's nominee through fast--if somebody on the Thomas-Trump-Turtle team kicks the bucket, the Rs will fight very hard to keep The Current Incumbent from filling the seat, so the Breyer patch needs to be dealt with quickly, just in case.

Republicans are critical of her record on some issues (e.g. saying she's too lenient in sentencing) but are still heaping praise on her credentials and intelligence. Reminiscent of Justice Barrett. So I don't see this failing
why would the reps fall on their sword when the tie breaker is the VPOUS?

Hearings starts to day and appears that is should fly through confirmation. All the reasoning from my previous forecast still stands. I would have expected if the Republicans were planning on making this a fight to gain political points with the base you would be hearing more about the confirmation in the media. I expect a straightforward confirmation.
With the confirmation hearing happening today, all signs point to a successful confirmation.

Given the hearing start today and the vote is hoped to take place prior to recess on 8th April, and a Democratic control of the senate with a deciding vote, it would seem this is very likely pending something unpredictable in the hearings themselves.
Up 20% since I've been below the consensus.
her hearing starting tomorrow (21March) - assuming 4 days of hearings - Sen. Schumer has stated plans to get on calendar early April
With hears starting tomorrow this seems on pace to be one of the faster confirmation processes.

As many other forecasters have mentioned, while the average time between nomination and confirmation has be 68 days, the average time between nomination and first hearing has been 41 days (i.e. more than half the time).

(no change) There were some earlier news items along the lines of black women demonstrating (not exactly the term I think) before the hearings. Such if too extreme might have unintended consequences. OTOH when I did a token search, it was no longer a leading article. Perhaps some are thinking strategically.

The GOP has nothing to gain by stalling until after the midterms. Holding the seat open for nearly three years is unrealistic, so why drag this out? As nominations rarely get struck down, the odds are high unless procedural issues delay the timing beyond May 1.
Not seeing any major pushback from conservative media on this and the low stakes for the GOP at this stage considering the Supreme Court make up. The main risk is procedural

This would be at the low end of the range for recent confirmations not counting Coney Barrett. Reluctance to make this a mid term election issue by republicans so unless they stall, within the range of normal process.

Hearings will begin 21MAR and Democratic leaders are setting a goal to confirm her by 08APR. With generally bipartisan support from what I understand (at least enough to be nominated) I don’t see this dragging out. (https://www.cnn.com/2022/03/02/politics/ketanji-brown-jackson-capitol-hill-meetings/index.html). This would tracks with the average timeframe required for Supreme Court Nominees from nomination to confirmation. (https://www.senate.gov/legislative/nominations/SupremeCourtNominations1789present.htm). By my count 26 of the last 67 (39%) Supreme Court Justices took longer than the 39 days which would end for Jackson on 08APR.

Up 20% to be closer to the consensus. Many things could slow down the process. (Whatever happens I won't be in the top 10 of the leaderboard.)
Seeing Republican opposition rhetoric ramp up and I think there is a real but low probability the nomination gets blocked (or drawn out) on the basis of her views on race, crime, etc..
My outside view is the confirmation rate since 1945 (73%), adjusted to the current sentiment.

"Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell told @hughhewitt Ketanji Brown Jackson will be "treated respectfully" during her confirmation hearing and added he thinks she is "highly likely" to be confirmed to the Supreme Court." https://twitter.com/DaniellaMicaela/status/1504444695736463362

41 days remaining and 13 days elapsed, so she would have to be confirmed in less than 54 days. Taking the outside view the base rate since 1975 is 68 days [2]. The last justice prior to Barrett to be confirmed in less than 54 days was Roberts in 2005 (so of those eventually confirmed that's 2 out of 7 or 29%) [1].

Initial Forecast 3/17: Confirmation hearings begin 3/21. Average confirmation time since 1975 has been 68 days which would exceed the end of the question. Last confirmation was Barrett who was quickly confirmed in 35 days which was fastest ever due to the impending election where Republicans were expecting to lose their majority. Don't expect a repeat. Jackson's confirmation requires all 50 democratic senators to approve and given the average length of time, this is improbable by May 1st.

If Jackson is confirmed I believe it will be relatively quickly given the precedent set by the last confirmation of a Supreme Court judge and that the confirmation will essentially come down to 2 senators. I think the question is mainly a matter of whether all democratic senators support Jackson or not.

Of the three GOP senators who voted for her confirmation to the DC circuit court (Graham, Murkowski, and Collins), only Collins is acting iffy (and i think that's just political theater). Even two GOP senators would almost assure her confirmation. (my first prediction was fueled by feelings, not by thinkings)

I was quick to vote this morning without doing my inside view due diligence -- it appears the push is being made to get the confirmation done before the April 8 departure / two week break. And they seem on pace. With no notable abscenes on the Democrats side it appears they have the votes to get it done efficiently. I do leave some margin of error for a Democrat flip / an issue to delay the process.

She is still going through vetting. Anything could still surface to show she is not a viable candidate. But also the Democrats have to persuade all 50 members to vote for her. Something they’ve been struggling with. Also 1 May is only 6 weeks away now so time is starting to run out for the question.
Outside view: 61 days between nomination and required approval date About 50% of past nominations have made it in that deadline About 25% of past nominations have failed to make it at all

I give this event a relatively high likelihood. The time it usually takes for a confirmation to go through is covered by the given window. Problems within the democratic party over this candidate look unlikely given the upcoming midterm elections, the stakes might be too high for dissent, even with Manchin. Republicans might not see it as worthwile to make take their issues with the process or the candidate herself to the centre stage, since there are more easily digestable narratives to attack their political opponents with. In this time during Joe Biden's presidency it is also unlikely that calls for a delay to a next term would emerge.

Outside rate for this for me is near-100%. Hearings start March 21, and there's 41 days between then and the question close. The time from start of judiciary committee hearings to confirmation by the Senate for the past 7 justices have all been <41 days. The longest was Kagan at 38. From a scheduling perspective 41 days is plenty of time, and Dick Durbin who chairs the Judiciary Committee has said there's "no reason to wait or delay" (https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/democrats-set-judge-jacksons-confirmation-hearings-march-21/story?id=83207791). The average time from nomination to start of hearings since Roberts is 41 days, and Jackson's wait was only 21, so he seems to be making good on that promise. Barring Durbin scheduling the Judiciary Committee vote super late for some reason, there shouldn't be an issue with timing.

Believe the average time it takes to confirm a justice from nomination is 67-70 days (Average / median). So that pushes past Feb 25. Given partisanship has eroded over the last few years, I'd lean towards a longer-than-usual nomination. Some good datapoints here: https://www.brookings.edu/blog/fixgov/2022/03/14/whats-ahead-for-ketanji-brown-jackson-heres-what-recent-history-suggests/ -- overall, seems slim this gets done by May 1
Third prediction
Females seem to all have relatively short timelines for confirmation, coupled with Brown’s previous confirmation success the odds seem very likely.

I counted 2 / 11 cases (18%) in the modern era that were confirmed so quickly after nomination. But the Senate appears to have a schedule to beat that timeline with hearings starting 21 March. So I guess I will give the schedule the benefit of the doubt and adjust sharply lower if delays appear.
There's no indication that any Democrat Senator will oppose her, and that's all that's needed for her confirmation, together if necessary with the Vice President's casting vote.

On the one hand, she doesn't mutiple credible allegations of sexual assault against her, but on the other hand she's a she, a non-white one at that and, worst of all, Senator McConnell is still in office.
It is 62 days from when Ketanji Brown Jackson when was first nominated on the 28/2/22 to the 30/4/22.
Fully expect hearings to be utilized as a showcase for expressing opposition to the values and goals of the Biden Administration.
Up 20% since the consensus is so high. Useful link by @zbucklyo below.

About 40 days from the expected start of the proceedings. Good piece by the Brookings Institute on how the confirmation process has taken longer as partisanship has increased - even Barrett's nomination took over 20 days, and that was rushed through as quickly as possible. Since the rush isn't needed here, and there are other big doings (e.g., Ukraine) this seems less than likely.

In the survey phase, I put something like 46% (Oh, how I wish I had saved ALL my forecasts to reduce noise!). It was clear to me that May 1 was just below the average length for even similar instances. But it seems I have missed certain things and things seem different here. My uncertainty remaining is for the historical instances of rejection, since I have almost ruled out withdrawals or lapses due to Congressional recess.
Initial, highly subjective forecast.

Going up based on the fact that the hearings are supposed to start next Monday as @AnotherWorld pointed out. It seems like Amy Coney Barrett, rather than a deviation from the norm. may have set a new precedent for what is considered quick.
Wow I did not take into consideration the time frame on the question I have to say no unless it happens between the 22-24 march
Hearings from the 22/24 of March

I think with so many larger issues going on (ie Covid, Russia-Ukraine, Inflation, etc.) I don't think it makes a whole lot of sense for this confirmation to become a big battle. Especially since this will be a Liberal Judge replacing a Liberal judge on a Conservative leaning court. It seems like there is not much to be gained from fighting the nominee unless a) there is something uniquely disqualifying about her we do not already know. (Unlikely as imagine she has been carefully vetted by the Biden team) or b) Republicans believe there are points to be gained with voters by fighting the confirmation.
So it looks like the confirmation hearing is scheduled to be relatively soon: https://edition.cnn.com/2022/03/02/politics/ketanji-brown-jackson-capitol-hill-meetings/index.html

Looking at the time it took for a nominated Justice to be confirmed by the Senate, having Ketanji Brown Jackson confirmed by the Senate before 1 May 2022 would be a quicker than average confirmation. I believe the democrats stated that they wanted at least some form of bipartisan support, and Republicans are likely to be annoying, which does not bode well for this question's timeline.
Hearings start on March 21 and unless there is some unexpected skeleton uncovered this should be pretty easy sailing, similar to Barrett

Initial forecast to be above the consensus. A comparison class might be the work the US Congress is getting done on some non-marquee 46 issues. I expect absent some bombshells (not a good word right now), that enough GOP Senators will tack to the normal "good idea to have both qualified and balanced" SCOTUS justices. YMMV
